  "prompt": "Why do jain sadhus do not wear clothes?",
  "response": "Jain Digambara monks (sadhus) traditionally practice a form of extreme asceticism that includes remaining naked as a way to demonstrate complete detachment from material possessions and worldly desires. This practice is rooted in several philosophical and spiritual principles:\n\n1. Absolute non-attachment\n- Nudity symbolizes complete renunciation of worldly possessions\n- Demonstrating freedom from material desires and physical comforts\n\n2. Spiritual purification\n- Rejecting clothing represents detachment from physical body and ego\n- Showing commitment to spiritual path and inner transformation\n\n3. Symbolic meaning\n- Nakedness represents spiritual equality\n- Indicates rejection of social status and material distinctions\n\n4. Philosophical interpretation\n- Represents living in a state of absolute vulnerability and humility\n- Demonstrates trust in divine providence\n\n5. Historical and scriptural basis\n- Follows teachings of Mahavira, the last Tirthankara of Jainism\n- Considered a way to practice extreme asceticism and non-possession\n\nIt's important to note that not all Jain monks practice complete nudity. Svetambara Jain monks wear white clothing, while Digambara monks practice sky-clad (nude) asceticism. This practice is limited to male monks and is not followed by female monks or lay Jains.",
